# Never use checkboxes — always use toggle switches

Raw `<input type="checkbox">` is banned in the UI. Every boolean control
(settings, options, "enable X", filters) must use the shared `Toggle`
switch component for a nicer UI.

- Panel dashboard: `import Toggle from '@/components/Toggle.vue'`
- It is `v-model` compatible (prop `modelValue`, emits `update:modelValue`).
- Make the adjacent label text clickable too (toggles are buttons, so a
  wrapping `<label>` won't forward the click).

```vue
<!-- ❌ BAD -->
<label class="flex items-center gap-2">
  <input v-model="form.enabled" type="checkbox" />
  <span>Enable feature</span>
</label>

<!-- ✅ GOOD -->
<div class="flex items-center gap-3">
  <Toggle v-model="form.enabled" />
  <span class="text-sm cursor-pointer" @click="form.enabled = !form.enabled">
    Enable feature
  </span>
</div>
```

This also covers checkboxes hand-styled as switches via `sr-only peer` —
use the `Toggle` component instead of re-implementing it.
